    "model_text": "Utah and Memphis offered contrasting playmaking blueprints, and the game swung when the Jazz sharpened their reads in the second half while the Grizzlies’ half-court creation thinned out under pressure.\n\nMemphis opened with a deliberate, two-hub approach: Mike Conley as the primary organizer and Marc Gasol as the release valve at the elbows. Early possessions flowed through angle pick-and-rolls and high-low touches, using Kyle Anderson as a connective passer to bend Utah’s shell. The Grizzlies emphasized paint touches and free throws, toggling Conley-Gasol dribble handoffs with secondary drives from Shelvin Mack and Dillon Brooks. Their playmaking was methodical more than explosive—probing for mid-range pockets and short-roll reads, with Conley manipulating pace to keep Gobert in a drop and Gasol as a late pop threat. The best stretch arrived mid–second and mid–third quarters when Memphis stacked stops, ran early offense, and let Conley attack a retreating defense; Gasol’s high-post facilitation added rhythm and drew fouls. But as Utah shrank driving lanes and switched more selectively on the wings, Memphis’ creation tilted toward self-creation. When Conley sat or the Jazz forced him off his spots, possessions bogged into contested pull-ups, late-clock isolations, and bailout free throws. Turnovers at the point of attack invited Jazz runouts and undercut Memphis’ half-court cadence.\n\nUtah’s playmaking identity was broader and more modular. Ricky Rubio and Joe Ingles shared table-setting duties early, toggling Spain actions, empty-corner pick-and-rolls, and swing-swing sequences to target weak-side help. Derrick Favors’ early seal-and-finish game gave them inside ballast, while Ingles punished soft closeouts and run-the-wheel actions to keep the ball ahead of the defense. The Jazz leaned on advantage passing—drive, draw, and kick—rather than one dominant initiator. As the game matured, Donovan Mitchell’s usage climbed; he shifted from early probing to late-clock shot creation and foul manufacture, stabilizing possessions when Memphis walled off first actions. Dante Exum and Alec Burks supplied secondary downhill pressure, especially in the third, where Exum’s straight-line drives collapsed the Grizzlies and produced free throws and kickouts. Critically, Utah’s playmaking adapted to Memphis’ physicality: they amped pace after stops, targeted cross-matches in early offense, and used Gobert as a vertical gravity hub. Fourth-quarter sequences repeatedly featured Mitchell/Exum rejecting screens, forcing tags, then hitting Gobert on dives or spraying to Ingles, whose late threes and foul draws were dagger moments.\n\nTempo and turnover math told the story. Memphis needed the game in the half court; when Utah’s perimeter length disrupted entry angles and Gobert sat back to erase rim attempts, Grizzlies’ creators defaulted to tougher shots. Utah, by contrast, diversified initiators and leaned into paint-to-three decisions. The late-game separation came from Jazz rim pressure converting to free throws and rhythm threes, while Memphis’ offense narrowed to Conley/Gasol solutions without enough weak-side creation to keep up. In a grind-it-out setting, Utah’s collective playmaking and vertical spacing outlasted Memphis’ more centralized model.",
