    "model_text": "Fresno State’s back-to-back against New Mexico offered a study in contrasting contexts and similar conclusions: in front of a packed Pit in Albuquerque, the Bulldogs absorbed an early Lobo surge and closed like a veteran group to win 81-73; a season later in an empty Save Mart Center, they ground through a defensive rock fight and survived in overtime, 64-62. Different tempos, same throughline—Fresno State’s poise in late-game possessions and a defense that tightened precisely when required.\n\nIn the Pit, New Mexico rode crowd energy to a 43-35 burst early in the second half, fueled by rim pressure, free throws, and second-chance touches. Fresno State’s response was decisive and methodical. The Bulldogs flattened the game with ball screens and isolation matchups, then attacked downhill to manufacture points at the stripe and step-in threes. Deshon Taylor was the organizer and closer—multiple paint touches, foul draws, and timely perimeter makes shifted control. When New Mexico clawed within a possession around the five-minute mark, Fresno answered with two hallmark sequences: a baseline drive that forced rotation and produced free throws, and a late-clock kick-out three that stretched the lead back to two possessions. From there, Fresno State managed the clock and whistle, winning the bonus game and sealing it with composure at the line.\n\nWhat separated the Bulldogs tactically was their middle-third spacing and willingness to invert matchups. They repeatedly dragged New Mexico’s bigs into space, then punished switches with straight-line drives and slot cuts. Defensively, they recalibrated at halftime—showing more dig help on post touches, closing air on New Mexico’s short-rolls, and turning the Lobos’ early paint feast into harder, off-balance finishes. New Mexico’s best counter—pounding the glass and living at the stripe—kept them afloat, but Fresno State’s shot diet improved as the game wore on while the Lobos’ devolved into tougher, contested twos. In a game that hinged on execution under duress, the Bulldogs’ veterans dictated pace in the final five minutes.\n\nThe return meeting in Fresno flipped the aesthetics. Points were scarce, rhythm fragile, and whistles frequent. New Mexico’s length flattened drives and disrupted first-side actions, while Fresno State leaned into a half-court attrition plan: pack the paint, wall the rim, and force jumpers late in the clock. Offensively, the Bulldogs were choppy for long stretches, but their best stretches mirrored the Albuquerque finish—ball-screen simplicity, two-man game in the slots, and patience to find cutters on the second side.\n\nThe decisive phase came after regulation at 53-53. Fresno won overtime by re-centering its identity—defensive rebounding, matchups hunted with purpose, and late-clock calm. A put-back and a strong-hand drive provided the initial cushion; free throws and one more stand at the rim closed the door. Where the regulation minutes swung on exchanged stops and empty trips, OT swung on Fresno State’s small execution edges: screening angles that freed the ball handler’s inside shoulder, quick outlets to beat pressure, and the discipline to contest without fouling on New Mexico’s rim attacks.\n\nAcross both games, several themes held. Fresno State’s late-game shot profile was superior—more paint touches leading to free throws or kick-outs, fewer early-clock contested jumpers. Defensively, the Bulldogs improved in-game at taking away New Mexico’s first options: they shrunk gaps after halftime in Albuquerque and sat on post entry angles in Fresno. Their guards controlled turnover pockets; when New Mexico threatened with momentum plays, Fresno answered by stabilizing possessions through the foul line. And the Bulldogs’ bench minutes—particularly on the defensive glass—were quietly pivotal in buying rest and maintaining physicality.\n\nCredit New Mexico for imposing different problems in each venue: pace, rim pressure and crowd-swing runs at the Pit; length, switching, and grinding half-court defense in Fresno. But in both instances, Fresno State dictated the last chapter. The Bulldogs didn’t need structural overhauls—just sharper purpose. When they simplified to their core actions and trusted their defense to finish possessions, they won the margins that decide conference games in February.\n\nTwo environments, two scripts, same outcome. Fresno State showed a veteran’s understanding of time, score, and whistle—why the paint, the stripe, and one extra pass matter most when the game tilts toward winning time.",
