    "model_text": "The BYU Cougars recently showcased their versatility and readiness for postseason play with a pair of contrasting victories over Texas Southern and San Francisco. While the win against the Tigers was a masterclass in offensive execution and perimeter shooting, the triumph over the Dons required a grittier, more physical approach to secure the crucial number two seed in the upcoming West Coast Conference tournament. Together, these performances highlight a team peaking at the right moment.\n\nAgainst Texas Southern, the Cougars' backcourt put on an absolute clinic, propelling BYU to an 87-71 victory. The story of the night was the historic shooting performance by Alex Barcello. The senior guard was untouchable from beyond the arc, becoming the first player in BYU history to hit seven consecutive three-pointers. Barcello finished with a career-high 27 points on a staggering 10-of-13 shooting from the field. Not to be outdone, his backcourt running mate, Brandon Averette, poured in 30 points, aggressively attacking the rim and hitting six threes of his own. The Tigers simply had no answer for the dual-threat posed by the Cougars' guards, who systematically dismantled the defense. The frontcourt provided solid support, with Matt Haarms anchoring the paint, allowing the guards the freedom to operate on the perimeter and dictating the tempo from the opening tip.\n\nThe subsequent matchup against San Francisco presented a starkly different challenge. The Dons forced the Cougars into a more physical, grind-it-out contest, testing BYU's resilience. In a game where the perimeter shots weren't falling with the same historic frequency, the Cougars relied on their depth and interior play to secure a 79-73 win. Freshman Caleb Lohner stepped up significantly, bringing essential energy and production to the starting lineup. Lohner's ability to battle on the boards and provide timely scoring was crucial in keeping the Dons at bay, particularly during stretches where the offense stagnated. Despite San Francisco making several runs in the second half to cut into the deficit, BYU maintained its composure. The Cougars executed effectively down the stretch, utilizing methodical ball movement and solid team defense to protect their lead and close out the game.\n\nThese back-to-back wins encapsulate the dual identity of Mark Pope's squad. They possess the explosive firepower to shoot opponents out of the gym, as evidenced against Texas Southern, but they also have the toughness to win ugly, possession-by-possession battles, as seen against San Francisco. With the #2 seed in the WCC tournament now locked up, BYU has proven they can adapt to different game scripts, making them a dangerous, multi-dimensional threat heading into March.",
