    "model_text": "BYU’s two-game stretch offered a clean look at Mark Pope’s preferred formula: a layered, veteran-driven offense that stretches you to the arc, then punishes rotations with size, glass work and rim deterrence. Against Texas Southern, the Cougars methodically widened separation behind a blistering guard performance and the vertical gravity of their frontcourt. Against San Francisco, they leaned on depth and late-game execution to navigate a rugged, possession-by-possession WCC grinder. The common thread was control—of tempo, of space and, ultimately, of scoreboard leverage.\n\nTexas Southern at BYU: spacing, pace, and a guard avalanche\nFrom the opening possessions BYU’s ball-screen offense produced clean paint touches and kickouts, and Texas Southern never found a consistent coverage answer. The Cougars’ early half-court rhythm was anchored by the high-low interplay with their 7-foot anchor sealing deep and screening into short rolls, complemented by staggered actions that freed shooters on the second side. Once BYU forced the Tigers to shrink the floor, the backcourt took over.\n\nBrandon Averette authored the decisive stretch. His downhill burst in middle ball screens, paired with confident pull-up threes, cracked the shell repeatedly. When TSU flattened to take away the lane, BYU flowed to drive-and-kick threes and snuck cutters behind ball-watching help. The result was a cascading run that turned a two-possession lead into a runway.\n\nDefensively, BYU won the math and the margins. They sat on Texas Southern’s initial actions, bodied drivers without over-helping, and finished possessions on the glass. The rim protection changed shot profiles—several Tigers forays ended in high-arcing bailouts—and BYU’s guards converted long rebounds into early offense. Free throws and second-chance points padded separation; once the Cougars got into the bonus, they strangled any comeback oxygen. The finishing touch was composure: even when TSU pieced together a late spurt, BYU answered with clock management, paint touches, and trips to the line. The final margin reflected both perimeter shot-making and interior control.\n\nSan Francisco at BYU: a WCC chess match decided by depth and late shot-making\nIf Texas Southern was about flow, San Francisco was about friction. USF’s compact, switch-and-scramble defense dragged BYU into tougher reads and fewer early-clock looks. The Dons fronted the post, pinched gaps, and tried to live with contested mid-range. BYU’s counter was patience and variety: empty-corner ball screens to isolate a matchup, post seals off duck-ins, and pindowns to free guards curling into space.\n\nMomentum swung in pockets. BYU’s bench delivered the first push—energy on the glass and a couple of timely threes stabilized an uneven opening quarter-hour. USF answered with pressure at the point of attack and dribble handoff counters that pulled BYU’s bigs into space, trimming the deficit at the half. The hinge came midway through the second: BYU’s defense strung together multiple stops by firming up at the nail and tagging rollers on time, then flipped the floor with quick outlets and deep advances. One sequence—contest, outlet, pitch-ahead three—captured the change in tempo and tone.\n\nFrom there, shot-making and discipline took over. Alex Barcello’s late threes were daggers born of structure: inside-out touches, extra pass, feet set. The bigs screened without slipping early, protected the rim without fouling, and cleaned the glass to deny USF the second looks they needed to extend possessions. Even foul trouble and a brief Dons surge couldn’t dislodge the Cougars once they established two-possession control; BYU executed end-of-game offense—flattened sets to drain clock, ball in the hands of best decision-makers, and free throws to close.\n\nThrough-line analysis\n- Shot quality control: BYU consistently engineered high-value attempts—corner threes, rolls at the rim, and paint touches that became free throws. Opponents were nudged toward contested pull-ups and late-clock heaves.\n- Interior leverage: The Cougars’ size didn’t just show in blocks and put-backs; it dictated schemes. Both Texas Southern and USF collapsed to protect the paint, and BYU’s perimeter feasted on the resulting airspace.\n- Backcourt stewardship: Averette’s burst and Barcello’s poise provided complementary gears—one to break the paint, the other to end possessions with efficient decisions. That duality insulated BYU from opponent runs.\n- Depth and role clarity: Rotations yielded tangible lift—rebounding, defensive versatility, and spot shooting—allowing BYU to win the middle minutes where many games tilt.\n\nNet: two wins built on shot profile superiority, rim protection, and closing-time composure. In different styles of game, BYU arrived at the same destination by dictating terms on both ends.",
