    "model_text": "Across the two tapes, Moses Wood’s offensive imprint was intermittent but telling—more a set of targeted flashes than a steady drumbeat.\n\nAgainst Wichita State, Wood functioned largely as a floor-spacing release valve in Tulane’s half-court. His most visible contribution came in the first half, where he knocked down a perimeter jumper in the left slot to trim the margin to 40–35 and briefly halt the Shockers’ surge. That make encapsulated his purpose: stretch the back line of Wichita State’s compact help and punish late closeouts. Beyond that moment, his touches were sporadic. Wichita State’s physical switches and ball pressure funneled Tulane’s possessions through guards and elbow actions, leaving Wood to live on second-side opportunities that rarely arrived in rhythm. He ran the lanes, lifted from the corner to the wing on drive-and-kick concepts, and screened to trigger guards downhill, but he wasn’t a primary option. The net result: a limited scoring footprint and minimal trips to the stripe, with his spacing value more theoretical than leveraged as the game tilted decisively toward the Shockers after halftime.\n\nVersus Houston, the assignment hardened and Wood’s offensive windows narrowed further. The Cougars’ point-of-attack heat and pristine rotations erased much of Tulane’s early-side action, and Wood’s touches came deeper in the clock, often against a set defense. He spotted to both corners and occasionally lifted to the wing to create a cleaner passing angle, but Houston chased shooters off the line and bodied cutters, forcing contested twos or rushed sprays. When Wood did spring free, his release was compact and confident; however, Houston’s contests were immediate, and make-or-miss variance skewed against him. Tulane’s best stretches came in transition and secondary breaks—moments when Wood ran to space and threatened as a trailer—but Houston’s dominance on the glass throttled those chances. The absence of sustained paint touches for Tulane also meant fewer inside-out threes for Wood, depriving him of the rhythm looks that typically fuel his efficiency.\n\nComparatively, Wichita State offered Wood a little more daylight on the arc, yielding his clearest scoring moment. Houston allowed almost none, turning him into a spacer who tilted help but seldom cashed in. Tactically, Tulane might have unlocked more by scripting early possessions for Wood—designing staggered exits or Spain actions to spring him above the break—rather than relying on improvised kick-outs against elite, connected defenses. As it stood, Wood’s offensive impact was subdued by context: limited volume, few clean catch-and-shoots, and defenses intent on winning the physicality and possession battles that generate his best looks.",
