    "model_text": "Arkansas’ rebounding told two very different stories across its Dec. 5 trip to Colorado State and its Dec. 20 home win over Oral Roberts, and those arcs help explain both game flows.\n\nOn Dec. 5 at Colorado State, Arkansas controlled the glass early by committee but didn’t overwhelm. The Razorbacks’ first-half advantage was built more on positional defense and first-shot stops than sheer volume on the boards. Daniel Gafford was quiet on the glass before halftime, and Colorado State’s Nico Carvacho—one of the nation’s sturdier rebounders—steadily worked his way into double figures by the stretch run (the broadcast noted 10 points, 10 rebounds late). Arkansas’ transition surge in the second half (spurred by pressure defense and live-ball turnovers) produced runouts rather than put-back chances; when the Razorbacks broke the game open from 67–60 to the final 98–74, it was pace and shot-making that separated them, not second-chance dominance. The on-screen keys to the game underscored Arkansas’ fast-break points and turnover margin, while Gafford’s final line (12 points, 8 rebounds) reflected an efficient but not overwhelming night on the glass. Net: solid team rebounding, acceptable containment of Carvacho, but no massive offensive rebounding imprint.\n\nBy contrast, Dec. 20 versus Oral Roberts evolved into a rebounding clinic—especially after halftime. Arkansas trailed for long stretches before flipping the game behind a decisive edge on the boards. The broadcast repeatedly highlighted the gap: Arkansas had 23 rebounds to ORU’s 11 during a first-half timeout, then extended the advantage to 30–16 by 3:40 of the second half and 38–14 by 1:34. Justin Smith was the tone-setter, stacking a double-double and drawing a late graphic note for clearing 10+ rebounds—the program’s first such effort since the Bobby Portis era. Arkansas’ guards also rebounded down aggressively; Devo Davis and Jalen Tate were active in traffic, converting long rebounds into immediate transition. The second-chance surge correlated with the decisive 8–0 and 11–0 runs out of the locker room, when Arkansas turned a 40–30 halftime deficit into a 75–66 lead and never looked back. Put-backs, tip-outs, and extended possessions bled ORU’s legs and flattened its spacing on the other end.\n\nComparative takeaways:\n- Defensive rebounding: Slight improvement. At CSU, Arkansas limited first looks reasonably well but conceded Carvacho’s positional boards. Against ORU, the Hogs vacuumed misses at all five spots—long rebounds included—denying second looks and fueling pace. The guards’ gang-rebounding was the clear upgrade.\n- Offensive rebounding: Marked improvement. There was little second-chance emphasis in Fort Collins; the separation came in transition. Versus ORU, Arkansas generated repeat shots throughout the second half, with Smith’s interior work and collective pursuit producing momentum-swinging put-backs and free throws.\n- Physicality and box-outs: Better discipline on Dec. 20. ORU was outmuscled after halftime, while CSU’s size and Carvacho’s technique muted Arkansas’ frontcourt advantage on Dec. 5.\n- Impact on outcomes: In Fort Collins, rebounding was complementary to Arkansas’ turnover pressure and three-point shooting. Against ORU, rebounding was the engine of the comeback and the game’s defining edge—Arkansas flipped both tempo and shot volume through the glass.\n\nBottom line: Arkansas regressed slightly in individual containment of an elite rebounder on Dec. 5 but showed no structural weakness. Two weeks later, the Razorbacks took a clear step forward, transforming rebounding into a winning identity—crushing the defensive glass, attacking the offensive boards, and using those extra possessions to throttle ORU after halftime.",
