    "model_text": "Navy’s glass work told two different stories across its early-season bookends. On Nov. 12 against Virginia Tech at the Veterans Classic, the Midshipmen were physically overmatched for long stretches, conceding deep post position and second-chance points as the Hokies’ front line, led by Keve Aluma and Justyn Mutts, carved out space. Virginia Tech repeatedly generated inside touches and free throws, a sign Navy was late to first-contact box outs and getting displaced on seals. The shot profile mattered: Tech’s balance of paint attempts and efficient perimeter shooting forced longer closeouts and left Navy in rotation, where weak-side checks broke down and guards were caught inside without inside leverage. The result was a steady Hokie advantage in 50-50s and team rebounds, with Navy’s best work on the boards coming in short mid-half spurts rather than sustained segments.\n\nBy Dec. 1 at Georgetown, Navy’s rebounding posture was markedly improved—particularly in the second half of a 78–71 upset. The Midshipmen tightened first-shot defense and, crucially, finished possessions. Their guards were active downhill to the dotted line on shots, tagging Georgetown’s rollers and cracking back to bodies. Forward rotations were crisper: early hits on Hoyas bigs limited deep catches, and Navy showed more discipline with inside-out box outs rather than chasing the ball. That translated to fewer put-backs for Georgetown during Navy’s decisive late-game run. Cam Davis’ shot-making headlined the night, but the platform was built on collective board work—gang rebounding that denied the Hoyas’ typical Big East-size advantage. Navy also controlled the defensive glass better after timeouts, a tell that Ed DeChellis’ staff emphasized matchups and responsibility on the fly.\n\nThe temporal pattern underscores the shift. Against Virginia Tech, momentum swung when the Hokies generated consecutive second chances; Navy’s defense bent after initial stops because the back-side wedge outs weren’t there. In Washington, sequences that could have tilted—late-clock Georgetown drives leading to traffic shots—ended with clean Navy rebounds, fueling composure and clock control. Navy’s bigs were stronger at carving space early in possessions, and the wings committed to inside positioning before the shot rather than reacting after the release.\n\nCausally, two factors drove the improvement: physicality at the hit point and guard participation. The Midshipmen’s perimeter players treated rebounding as a five-man job, which muted Georgetown’s size and kept loose balls in Navy hands. Scheme-wise, Navy showed more drop coverage and fewer hard hedges than it used at times versus Virginia Tech; with fewer long recoveries, box-out assignments were clearer and bodies were nearer the rim when the shot went up.\n\nNet assessment:\n- Improvement on Dec. 1: Defensive rebounding security, especially in late-game, high-leverage possessions; better early contact and weak-side tags; enhanced guard rebounding commitment; cleaner scheme leading to fewer scramble situations.\n- Regression from Nov. 12 baseline: Limited—if anything, Nov. 12 exposed issues (deep seals, late tags) that were largely corrected by Dec. 1.\n- Impact: By denying second chances at Georgetown, Navy controlled tempo and leveraged made shots into set defenses, a key ingredient in closing out a high-major road win. Against Virginia Tech, the inability to finish possessions compounded scoring droughts and allowed the Hokies to stretch separation.\n\nIn short, Navy evolved from sporadic, undersized resilience on Nov. 12 to organized, collective rebounding toughness on Dec. 1—turning the glass from a liability into a winning edge.",
