    "model_text": "Wichita State’s Dec. 2 win over Oral Roberts and its Nov. 13 grind past South Alabama offered a clear window into the Shockers’ evolving identity on the glass. The contrast was instructive: against ORU, Wichita State labored through long stretches of defensive-rebounding slippage and second-chance leakage before stabilizing late; versus South Alabama, the Shockers turned rebounding into a situational weapon—especially in the final eight minutes—using physicality to seal the game.\n\nAgainst Oral Roberts, the early warning signs came quickly. ORU’s spread pick‑and‑roll and five-out spacing pulled Wichita State’s bigs away from the lane, exposing weak‑side blockouts. The Eagles lived on long rebounds off high-volume threes and timely dives, manufacturing put-backs and bonus trips that fueled multiple mini-runs (notably the 57–50 and 66–65 stretches). Wichita State’s initial shots contested well enough, but first-contact box-outs were late, and guards were caught ball-watching. The Shockers eventually adjusted—tagging rollers earlier, dropping a guard to the nail to crack back on the weak side, and sending a second body to the restricted area on long launches. The payoff was a steadier final five minutes, when consecutive one-and-done stops and two critical late put-backs swung the closing possessions. Still, the aggregate picture: too many free second chances conceded, with the Shockers’ rebounding control arriving more as game management than baseline dominance.\n\nThe Nov. 13 South Alabama game presented a different challenge—a bigger, more vertical, rim-seeking opponent—and Wichita State’s response was more structurally sound. The Shockers were sharper on first contact, wedging out the block and walling without fouling through the second half’s middle third. When the game tightened at 51–51 and into the low 60s, their guards committed to gang rebounding: the wings pinched down from the arc, and the point guard routinely dropped below the foul line on shots to clean up long caroms. That collective effort limited the Jaguars’ second-chance lifelines during a pivotal 9–2 Wichita State push, and the Shockers added timely offensive boards that either produced free throws or reset clock in a two‑possession game. In short, they turned rebound moments into momentum plays.\n\nComparatively, Dec. 2 was a regression in defensive rebounding poise through the middle 20 minutes—spacing and pace from ORU exposed box-out discipline and the Shockers’ late help was sporadic until crunch time. Nov. 13 showed a clearer plan and better commitment to five-man rebounding principles, especially versus a more traditional paint attack. On the offensive glass, both games featured opportunistic work, but South Alabama saw more purposeful crashes from the slot and dunker spot, while ORU’s transition threat occasionally deterred full commits.\n\nCausally, opponent style mattered: ORU’s perimeter gravity produced long rebounds that guards must claim; Wichita State was slow to recalibrate. South Alabama’s size invited classic hit-and-get fundamentals that suit the Shockers’ physical profile. Coaching adjustments also told: the ORU finish improved once Wichita State flattened the coverage and assigned a guard to the weak‑side check; against South Alabama, that emphasis was present earlier and sustained longer.\n\nNet assessment: Wichita State’s rebounding baseline is sturdy when the task is traditional paint protection and blockouts; it’s less reliable against stretch offenses that create long misses and scramble rotations. The Dec. 2 close suggests the lessons are landing—late-game urgency restored the glass. For the next step, the Shockers need earlier guard engagement on long rebounds and more consistent weak‑side tags to prevent opponents like ORU from living on second chances.",
