    "model_text": "Texas A&M guard Quenton Jackson’s shot profile and efficiency told two very different stories across the Aggies’ Jan. 8 win at Arkansas and the Mar. 12 SEC Tournament semifinal against the Razorbacks. The tape shows a January performance built on downhill, whistle-drawing efficiency and late-game poise, contrasted with a March effort that layered in confident perimeter shot-making and volume, scaling his impact as A&M surged to a decisive semifinal victory.\n\nOn Jan. 8 in College Station, Jackson’s scoring came primarily at the rim and the stripe. Early possessions featured straight-line drives and secondary breaks where he attacked closeouts, absorbing contact and living at the foul line. His jumper was largely a pressure-release, not the engine. The pivotal sequence arrived inside the final minute: protecting a one-possession lead, Jackson coolly buried two free throws with 14.5 seconds left to make it a two-possession game, then added two more with 9.7 remaining to ice an 86–81 win. The mechanics were compact, tempo steady, with no drift—indicative of a player deeply comfortable closing games via the line. Shot selection skewed high-value: paint touches, transition pushes, and late-clock drives. Arkansas never forced him into a diet of contested pull-ups; instead, he chose contact over comfort, and it paid off.\n\nTwo months later in Tampa, Jackson expanded the scoring bandwidth. A&M’s 82–64 semifinal rout over Arkansas featured a broader mix: catch-and-shoot threes, mid-range pull-ups, and the same physical rim pressure. Early in the first half, he splashed a right-wing three in rhythm, then balanced that with strong-side drives culminating in body-control finishes. In the second half, the perimeter confidence held—he stepped into another triple and continued to hunt space in semi-transition. The free-throw reliability remained a constant; he drew contact late and knocked down key attempts to extend the margin. The notable change was the comfort taking and making jumpers without losing efficiency—a regression risk that never materialized. His release was decisive, footwork clean on relocations, and he avoided over-dribbling into traffic, a common Arkansas trap.\n\nKey improvements:\n- Perimeter threat added to the toolkit. In March, Jackson’s willingness and success from three altered Arkansas’ help principles. The Hogs couldn’t load the lane with the same aggression, opening driving seams for both Jackson and teammates.\n- Shot versatility and volume. January’s profile was rim-and-FT heavy; March layered spot-up threes and rhythm pull-ups, enabling scoring in multiple segments—set offense, early offense, and late clock.\n- Pace control. Jackson toggled between burst and patience, particularly after timeouts, flowing into actions that produced clean catch-and-shoot looks rather than forcing contested twos.\n\nConstants that translated:\n- Elite foul-line composure. Both games ended with Jackson sealing possessions at the stripe; his routine, arc, and follow-through were identical and trustworthy.\n- Straight-line power to the cup. Even with improved jumper usage in March, he didn’t drift into low-percentage isolation fadeaways; he still prioritized paint touches.\n\nWhat regressed:\n- Little, if anything, in pure shooting terms. The March film doesn’t show detrimental heat-checks or rushed attempts. Turnover risk rose briefly when Arkansas amped ball pressure, but it didn’t bleed into shot selection.\n\nContext and impact:\n- January’s jumper-light approach fit a tight whistle-driven game that required clutch free throws. In March, A&M’s broader offensive rhythm invited Jackson to scale up his perimeter usage, and he punished soft gaps with confident makes. The added spacing effect was tangible: Arkansas’ backline rotations were later, A&M’s secondary scorers found pockets, and the Aggies controlled scoreboard pressure for most of the second half.\n\nBottom line: Jackson evolved from a rim-and-line closer in January to a three-level scorer in March. The improvement wasn’t cosmetic; it strategically reshaped Arkansas’ defense and underpinned A&M’s semifinal separation.",
